**$explain Verbosity Levels:**

| Level | Information Provided | Use Case |
|-------|---------------------|----------|
| **`queryPlanner`** | Query plan selection | Understanding index selection |
| **`executionStats`** | Execution metrics and timing | Performance analysis |
| **`allPlansExecution`** | All considered plans | Debugging query optimizer |

**Key $explain Metrics:**

| Metric | Good Value | Bad Value | Action |
|--------|------------|-----------|--------|
| **executionTimeMillis** | < 100ms | > 1000ms | Optimize indexes |
| **totalDocsExamined** | Close to returned | Much higher than returned | Improve selectivity |
| **stage** | IXSCAN | COLLSCAN | Create indexes |
| **indexesUsed** | Appropriate index | None or wrong index | Review index strategy |

**$hint Use Cases:**

| Scenario | Purpose | Example |
|----------|---------|--------|
| **Performance Testing** | Compare different indexes | `.hint({ field: 1 })` |
| **Override Poor Choice** | Force better index | `.hint({ compound: 1, index: -1 })` |
| **Debugging** | Force collection scan | `.hint({ $natural: 1 })` |
| **Specific Requirements** | Ensure index usage | `.hint({ status: 1 })` |

**Best Practices:**
- **Use `executionStats`** for performance analysis
- **Monitor `totalDocsExamined` vs `totalDocsReturned`** ratio
- **Use `$hint` sparingly** - query optimizer is usually correct
- **Test with real data volumes** - small datasets can be misleading
- **Analyze slow queries regularly** using database profiler
- **Create compound indexes** matching query patterns
- **Drop unused indexes** to save space and improve write performance

**MongoDB Advanced Architecture** focuses on **Sharding** (horizontal scaling) and **Replication** (high availability). These are fundamental concepts for building robust, scalable MongoDB deployments.

## **1. Replication - High Availability & Data Redundancy**

```javascript
// Replica Set Configuration Example
// A replica set is a group of MongoDB servers maintaining the same dataset

// 1. Initialize a replica set
rs.initiate({
    _id: "myReplicaSet",
    members: [
        { _id: 0, host: "mongodb1.example.com:27017", priority: 2 }, // Primary preference
        { _id: 1, host: "mongodb2.example.com:27017", priority: 1 }, // Secondary
        { _id: 2, host: "mongodb3.example.com:27017", priority: 1 }, // Secondary
        { _id: 3, host: "mongodb4.example.com:27017", arbiterOnly: true } // Arbiter
    ]
});

// 2. Check replica set status
rs.status();

// 3. Add a new member
rs.add("mongodb5.example.com:27017");

// 4. Remove a member
rs.remove("mongodb5.example.com:27017");

// 5. Configure read preferences
const mongoose = require('mongoose');

// Connection with read preference
mongoose.connect('mongodb://mongodb1.example.com:27017,mongodb2.example.com:27017,mongodb3.example.com:27017/myapp?replicaSet=myReplicaSet', {
    readPreference: 'secondaryPreferred', // Try secondary first, fallback to primary
    w: 'majority', // Write concern - wait for majority acknowledgment
    j: true // Journal write concern
});

// 6. Read preference examples
const readPreferences = {
    primary: "Only from primary (default, strongest consistency)",
    primaryPreferred: "Primary first, fallback to secondary",
    secondary: "Only from secondaries (may read stale data)",
    secondaryPreferred: "Secondary first, fallback to primary",
    nearest: "Lowest network latency regardless of type"
};

// Application-level read preference
const User = mongoose.model('User', userSchema);

// Read from secondary for analytics
const analyticsData = await User.find({
    createdAt: { $gte: new Date('2024-01-01') }
}).read('secondary');

// Critical reads from primary
const criticalData = await User.findById(userId).read('primary');
```

## **2. Sharding - Horizontal Scaling**

```javascript
// Sharding distributes data across multiple servers (shards)
// Each shard is typically a replica set for high availability

// 1. Sharded Cluster Components Setup

// Config Servers (store metadata)
// Start config servers as replica set
mongod --configsvr --replSet configReplSet --port 27019 --dbpath /data/configdb

// Mongos (query router)
// Start mongos processes
mongos --configdb configReplSet/config1.example.com:27019,config2.example.com:27019,config3.example.com:27019 --port 27017

// Shard Servers (data storage)
// Each shard is a replica set
mongod --shardsvr --replSet shard1ReplSet --port 27018 --dbpath /data/shard1

// 2. Initialize sharded cluster
// Connect to mongos and add shards
sh.addShard("shard1ReplSet/shard1-a.example.com:27018,shard1-b.example.com:27018,shard1-c.example.com:27018");
sh.addShard("shard2ReplSet/shard2-a.example.com:27018,shard2-b.example.com:27018,shard2-c.example.com:27018");
sh.addShard("shard3ReplSet/shard3-a.example.com:27018,shard3-b.example.com:27018,shard3-c.example.com:27018");

// 3. Enable sharding for database
sh.enableSharding("ecommerce");

// 4. Choose shard key and shard collection
// Shard key determines how data is distributed
db.orders.createIndex({ customerId: 1, orderDate: 1 }); // Compound shard key
sh.shardCollection("ecommerce.orders", { customerId: 1, orderDate: 1 });

// 5. Shard key selection examples
const shardKeyStrategies = {
    userId: {
        pros: ["Even distribution if users are evenly distributed", "Queries by user are efficient"],
        cons: ["Hotspots if some users are very active", "Range queries may hit multiple shards"]
    },
    timestamp: {
        pros: ["Good for time-series data", "Chronological queries are efficient"],
        cons: ["All writes go to one shard (latest time)", "Creates hotspots"]
    },
    hashedUserId: {
        pros: ["Even distribution guaranteed", "Eliminates hotspots"],
        cons: ["Range queries hit all shards", "No query locality"]
    },
    compound: {
        pros: ["Balanced distribution and query efficiency", "Supports both equality and range queries"],
        cons: ["More complex to design", "Must include shard key in queries"]
    }
};

// 6. Monitoring sharded cluster
sh.status(); // Overall cluster status
db.stats(); // Database statistics across shards
db.collection.getShardDistribution(); // Data distribution per shard

// 7. Application considerations for sharding
const mongoose = require('mongoose');

// Connect to mongos routers
mongoose.connect('mongodb://mongos1.example.com:27017,mongos2.example.com:27017/ecommerce');

// Queries must include shard key for efficiency
const Order = mongoose.model('Order', orderSchema);

// Efficient query (includes shard key)
const userOrders = await Order.find({
    customerId: userId, // Shard key field
    status: 'pending'
});

// Inefficient query (missing shard key - scatter-gather)
const expensiveOrders = await Order.find({
    amount: { $gt: 1000 } // No shard key - hits all shards
});
```

**Architecture Comparison:**

| Aspect | Replication | Sharding |
|--------|-------------|----------|
| **Primary Purpose** | High availability, data redundancy | Horizontal scaling, increased capacity |
| **Data Distribution** | Same data on all nodes | Different data on each shard |
| **Scaling Type** | Vertical (read scaling) | Horizontal (read + write scaling) |
| **Complexity** | Low to Medium | High |
| **Failure Handling** | Automatic failover | Depends on shard and replica set health |
| **Query Routing** | Client chooses read preference | Mongos routes based on shard key |
| **Use Case** | Small to medium datasets | Large datasets (> TB) |

**Replication Components:**

| Component | Role | Characteristics |
|-----------|------|----------------|
| **Primary** | Accepts all writes | Only one per replica set |
| **Secondary** | Replicates from primary | Can serve reads (with read preference) |
| **Arbiter** | Voting only, no data | Helps with election, minimal resources |
| **Hidden** | Data replica, no reads | Backup, analytics without affecting production |
| **Delayed** | Delayed replication | Protection against operator errors |

**Sharding Components:**

| Component | Role | Characteristics |
|-----------|------|----------------|
| **Mongos** | Query router | Directs queries to appropriate shards |
| **Config Servers** | Metadata storage | Store cluster metadata, shard mappings |
| **Shards** | Data storage | Usually replica sets, store data chunks |
| **Shard Key** | Distribution strategy | Determines how data is partitioned |

