**When to Use Each Architecture:**

| Scenario | Replication | Sharding | Both |
|----------|-------------|----------|------|
| **High Availability Required** | ‚úÖ Essential | ‚ùå Not primary purpose | ‚úÖ Best of both |
| **Read Scaling** | ‚úÖ Read from secondaries | ‚úÖ Distribute across shards | ‚úÖ Maximum read capacity |
| **Write Scaling** | ‚ùå Limited to primary | ‚úÖ Distribute across shards | ‚úÖ Highest write capacity |
| **Dataset < 1TB** | ‚úÖ Sufficient | ‚ùå Overkill | ‚ùå Unnecessary complexity |
| **Dataset > 10TB** | ‚ùå Single server limits | ‚úÖ Necessary | ‚úÖ Production standard |
| **Global Distribution** | ‚úÖ Regional replicas | ‚úÖ Geographic sharding | ‚úÖ Optimal solution |
| **Development/Testing** | ‚úÖ Simple setup | ‚ùå Too complex | ‚ùå Replication sufficient |

**Best Practices:**

1. **Start with Replication**: Always use replica sets, even for single-server deployments
2. **Plan Shard Key Carefully**: Cannot be changed easily after sharding
3. **Monitor Shard Balance**: Ensure even data distribution
4. **Use Appropriate Read Preferences**: Balance consistency vs performance
5. **Test Failover Scenarios**: Practice disaster recovery procedures
6. **Monitor Performance**: Track query performance across shards
7. **Consider Zones**: Use zone sharding for geographic distribution
